# Introduction to Django

---

## How to create a new Django project

To create a new Django project, run:

`$ django-admin startproject <project_name>`

Which will create the following project structure:

```
project_name/
    manage.py
    mysite/
        __init__.py
        settings.py
        urls.py
        asgi.py
        wsgi.py
```

## Django project file structure

### project_name/

The outerÂ `project_name/`Â directory is a container for your project. 

Its name doesnâ€™t matter to Django; you can rename it to anything you like.

### project_name/manage.py

The `[manage.py](http://manage.py)` file is a command-line utility that lets you interact with your Django project in various ways via the CLI. 

### project_name/project_name/

The innerÂ `project_name/project_name/` directory is the actual Python package for your project. Its name is the Python package name youâ€™ll need to use to import anything inside it.

### mysite/__init__.py

**`mysite/__init__.py`** is an empty file that tells Python that this directory should be considered a Python package. 

â€¦

- **`mysite/settings.py`**: Settings/configuration for this Django project.Â [Django settings](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.2/topics/settings/)Â will tell you all about how settings work.
- **`mysite/urls.py`**: The URL declarations for this Django project; a â€œtable of contentsâ€ of your Django-powered site. You can read more about URLs inÂ [URL dispatcher](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.2/topics/http/urls/).
- **`mysite/asgi.py`**: An entry-point for ASGI-compatible web servers to serve your project. SeeÂ [How to deploy with ASGI](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.2/howto/deployment/asgi/)Â for more details.
- **`mysite/wsgi.py`**: An entry-point for WSGI-compatible web servers to serve your project. SeeÂ [How to deploy with WSGI](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.2/howto/deployment/wsgi/)Â for more details.

## Django **Projects vs. Django apps**

Whatâ€™s the difference between a project and an app? 

An app is a web application that does something â€“ e.g., a blog system, a database of public records or a small poll app. 

A project is a collection of configuration and apps for a particular website. 

<aside>
ğŸ“ A project can contain multiple apps. An app can be in multiple projects.

</aside>

**Create a new Django project with:**

`python manage.py startproject <project-name>`

**Create a new Django app with:**

`python manage.py startapp <app-name>`

## Django Overview

When a user requests a URL in their browser to a website/app built on Django, here is what happens:

1. Django receives the URL, checks theÂ `urls.py`Â file, and calls the view that matches the URL.
2. The view, located inÂ `views.py`, checks for relevant models, located in the `models.py` file
3. The models are imported from theÂ `models.py`Â file.
4. The view then sends the data to a specified HTML template in theÂ `template/`Â folder.
5. The template contains HTML and Django tags, and with the data it returns finished HTML content back to the browser.